paragraphs.title: Load ORE library
paragraphs.text:
%r

library(ORE)
options(ore.warn.order=FALSE)
options(width = 200)

paragraphs.title: Create a database table from a data.frame and get proxy object
paragraphs.text:
%r

tryCatch({ore.drop(table="IRIS")})

ore.create(iris, table = "IRIS")

cat("Class: ", class(IRIS))
cat("\nShape: ", dim(IRIS))

msg.data:
Class:  ore.frame
Shape:  150 5

paragraphs.text:

ore.ls()

paragraphs.title: Use overloaded dplyr functions to operate on ore.frames
paragraphs.text:
%r

library(magrittr)
library(OREdplyr)  # OREdplyr must be explicitly loaded to use

select(IRIS, Sepal.Length,Sepal.Width,Species) %>% head()     # select columns


RES <- select(IRIS, -Species) %>% head()                      # exclude columns
colnames(RES)

dim(IRIS)
filter(IRIS, Sepal.Length > 5, Species == 'setosa') %>% dim() # filter rows

paragraphs.title: Joining data - merge in R
paragraphs.text:
%r

df1 <- data.frame(x1=1:5, y1=letters[1:5])
df2 <- data.frame(x2=5:1, y2=letters[11:15])


merge (df1, df2, by.x="x1", by.y="x2")

paragraphs.title: Create tables and merge ore.frames
paragraphs.text:
%r

ore.drop(table="TEST_DF1")
ore.drop(table="TEST_DF2")

ore.create(df1, table="TEST_DF1")
ore.create(df2, table="TEST_DF2")

merge (TEST_DF1, TEST_DF2, by.x="x1", by.y="x2")

paragraphs.title: Store R objects in database datastore
paragraphs.text:
%r

ore.save(iris, name = "myDatastore", overwrite = TRUE) # save an R data.frame
list <- list(a = 1, b = TRUE, c = "oracle")            # create a list of values
ore.save(list, name = "myDatastore", append = TRUE)    # save list in the same datastore

ore.datastore()

paragraphs.text:
%md
## Machine Learning

msg.data: Machine Learning

paragraphs.title: Build an in-database Random Forest model to predict Species - returns a model proxy object
paragraphs.text:
%r

MOD.RF <- ore.odmRF(Species~., IRIS)   

summary(MOD.RF)

paragraphs.title: Use in-database model to make predictions using model proxy object
paragraphs.text:
%r

PRED <- predict(MOD.RF, IRIS, type=c("class","raw"), supplemental.cols="Species") 

head(PRED)

paragraphs.title: Store user-defined R function in database R script repository
paragraphs.text:
%r

ore.scriptCreate("RandomRedDots", RandomRedDots, overwrite=TRUE) 

ore.scriptList("RandomRedDots")

msg.data:
A data.frame: 1 x 2
NAMESCRIPT
<chr><chr>
RandomRedDotsfunction (numDots = 100) { id <- 1:10 plot(1:numDots, rnorm(numDots), pch = 21, bg = "red", cex = 2) data.frame(id = id, val = id/100) }

paragraphs.title: Run named UDF in a database-spawned R engine, passing function name and argument
paragraphs.text:
%r

res <- NULL
res <- ore.doEval(FUN.NAME="RandomRedDots", numDots=100)
res

paragraphs.title: Use OML4R-supported data parallelism to build one linear model per species
paragraphs.text:
%r

modList <- ore.groupApply(X=IRIS,
                          INDEX=IRIS$Species,
                          function(dat) {
                            lm(Sepal.Length ~ Sepal.Width + Petal.Length + Petal.Width, dat)
                          },
                          parallel = 2)

modList

paragraphs.text:
%md

## SQL API for embedded R execution

To use the SQL API for embedded R execution, a UDF must reside in the OML4R script repository, and an Oracle Machine Learning (OML) cloud account USERNAME PASSWORD and URL must be provided for an authentication token. The OUT_FMT parameter controls the format of output returned by the embedded R execution functions. The supported output formats are:

- JSON
- Relational
- XML
- PNG
- Asynchronous Mode Output

  • Asynchronous Mode Output

paragraphs.title: Create access details table to support token acquisition

paragraphs.text:
%md

OML4R provides APIs to persist the authorization token for use with the upcoming SQL calls:

- The `rqSetAuthToken` procedure sets the access token in the token store.
- The `rqIsTokenSet` function confirms if the authorization token status.
- 
The following example shows how to set the token in the token store and confirm it's status. A token has a lifecycle of 3600 seconds, or 1 hour, and it can be refreshed for up to 8 hours.

paragraphs.title: Asynchronous Output
paragraphs.text:
%md
_______________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
When a function is run asynchronously, it's run as a job which can be polled by using the `rqJobStatus` and `rqJobResult` functions. The following example shows how to submit an asynchronous job with XML output. JSON, PNG and relational outputs are also suppoted.

msg.data: When a function is run asynchronously, it's run as a job which can be polled by using the rqJobStatus and rqJobResult functions. The following example shows how to submit an asynchronous job with XML output. JSON, PNG and relational outputs are also suppoted.

paragraphs.title: Submit asynchronous job
paragraphs.text:
%script

set long 500

SELECT * FROM table(rqEval2(
    par_lst => '{"ore_async_flag":true, "ore_graphics_flag":true, "ore_service_level":"LOW"}',
    out_fmt => NULL,
    scr_name => 'RandomRedDots'));
